        {
          "nativeId": "feed",
          "name": "Feed",
          "aliases": [],
          "summary": {
            "text": "A feed is a section of a page that automatically loads new sections of content as the user scrolls. The sections of content in a feed are presented in article elements. So, a feed can be thought of as a dynamic list of articles that often appears to scroll infinitely.",
            "url": "https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/feed/#about"
          },
          "kind": "pattern",
          "canonicalUrl": "https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/feed/",
          "sections": [
            {
              "nativeId": "about",
              "title": "About This Pattern",
              "url": "https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/feed/#about",
              "content": null
            },
            {
              "nativeId": "examples",
              "title": "Example",
              "url": "https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/feed/#examples",
              "content": null
            },
            {
              "nativeId": "keyboard_interaction",
              "title": "Keyboard Interaction",
              "url": "https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/feed/#keyboard_interaction",
              "content": "The feed pattern is not based on a desktop GUI widget so the feed role is not associated with any well-established keyboard conventions.\nSupporting the following, or a similar, interface is recommended.\nWhen focus is inside the feed:\n• Page Down : Move focus to next article.\n• Page Up : Move focus to previous article.\n• Control + End : Move focus to the first focusable element after the feed.\n• Control + Home : Move focus to the first focusable element before the feed.\nNote\n• Due to the lack of convention, providing easily discoverable keyboard interface documentation is especially important.\n• In some cases, a feed may contain a nested feed.\nFor example, an article in a social media feed may contain a feed of comments on that article.\nTo navigate the nested feed, users first move focus inside the nested feed.\nOptions for supporting nested feed navigation include:\n• Users move focus into the nested feed from the content of the containing article with Tab .\nThis may be slow if the article contains a significant number of links, buttons, or other widgets.\n• Provide a key for moving focus from the elements in the containing article to the first item in the nested feed, e.g., Alt + Page Down .\n• To continue reading the outer feed, Control + End moves focus to the next article in the outer feed.\n• In the rare circumstance that a feed article contains a widget that uses the above suggested keys, the feed navigation key will operate the contained widget, and the user needs to move focus to an element that does not utilize the feed navigation keys in order to navigate the feed."
            },
            {
              "nativeId": "roles_states_properties",
              "title": "WAI-ARIA Roles, States, and Properties",
              "url": "https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/feed/#roles_states_properties",
              "content": "• The element that contains the set of feed articles has role feed .\n• If the feed has a visible label, the feed element has aria-labelledby referring to the element containing the title.\nOtherwise, the feed element has a label specified with aria-label .\n• Each unit of content in a feed is contained in an element with role article .\nAll content inside the feed is contained in an article element.\n• Each article element has aria-labelledby referring to elements inside the article that can serve as a distinguishing label.\n• It is optional but strongly recommended for each article element to have aria-describedby referring to one or more elements inside the article that serve as the primary content of the article.\n• Each article element has aria-posinset set to a value that represents its position in the feed.\n• Each article element has aria-setsize set to a value that represents either the total number of articles that have been loaded or the total number in the feed, depending on which value is deemed more helpful to users.\nIf the total number in the feed is undetermined, it can be represented by a aria-setsize value of -1 .\n• When article elements are being added to or removed from the feed container, and if the operation requires multiple DOM operations, the feed element has aria-busy set to true during the update operation.\nNote that it is extremely important that aria-busy is set to false when the operation is complete or the changes may not become visible to some assistive technology users."
            }
          ],
          "links": [
            {
