        {
          "nativeId": "grid",
          "name": "Grid (Interactive Tabular Data and Layout Containers)",
          "aliases": [],
          "summary": {
            "text": "A grid widget is a container that enables users to navigate the information or interactive elements it contains using directional navigation keys, such as arrow keys, Home , and End . As a generic container widget that offers flexible keyboard navigation, it can serve a wide variety of needs. It can be used for purposes as simple as grouping a collection of checkboxes or navigation links or as complex as creating a full-featured spreadsheet application. While the words \"row\" and \"column\" are used in the names of WAI-ARIA attributes and by assistive technologies when describing and presenting the logical structure of elements with the grid role, using the grid role on an element does not necessarily imply that its visual presentation is tabular.",
            "url": "https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/grid/#about"
          },
          "kind": "pattern",
          "canonicalUrl": "https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/grid/",
          "sections": [
            {
              "nativeId": "about",
              "title": "About This Pattern",
              "url": "https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/grid/#about",
              "content": null
            },
            {
              "nativeId": "examples",
              "title": "Examples",
              "url": "https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/grid/#examples",
              "content": null
            },
            {
              "nativeId": "dataGrid",
              "title": "Data Grids For Presenting Tabular Information",
              "url": "https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/grid/#dataGrid",
              "content": null
            },
            {
              "nativeId": "layoutGrid",
              "title": "Layout Grids for Grouping Widgets",
              "url": "https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/grid/#layoutGrid",
              "content": null
            },
            {
              "nativeId": "gridNav",
              "title": "Keyboard Interaction - Setting Focus and Navigating Inside Cells",
              "url": "https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/grid/#gridNav",
              "content": null
            },
            {
              "nativeId": "roles_states_properties",
              "title": "WAI-ARIA Roles, States, and Properties",
              "url": "https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/grid/#roles_states_properties",
              "content": "• The grid container has role grid .\n• Each row container has role row and is either a DOM descendant of or owned by the grid element or an element with role rowgroup .\n• Each cell is either a DOM descendant of or owned by a row element and has one of the following roles:\n• columnheader if the cell contains a title or header information for the column.\n• rowheader if the cell contains title or header information for the row.\n• gridcell if the cell does not contain column or row header information.\n• If there is an element in the user interface that serves as a label for the grid, aria-labelledby is set on the grid element with a value that refers to the labelling element.\nOtherwise, a label is specified for the grid element using aria-label .\n• If the grid has a caption or description, aria-describedby is set on the grid element with a value referring to the element containing the description.\n• If the grid provides sort functions, aria-sort is set to an appropriate value on the header cell element for the sorted column or row as described in the\nGrid and Table Properties Practice .\n• If the grid supports selection, when a cell or row is selected, the selected element has aria-selected set true .\nIf the grid supports column selection and a column is selected, all cells in the column have aria-selected set to true .\n• If the grid provides content editing functionality and contains cells that may have edit capabilities disabled in certain conditions, aria-readonly may be set true on cells where editing is disabled.\nIf edit functions are disabled for all cells, aria-readonly may be set true on the grid element.\nGrids that do not provide editing functions do not include the aria-readonly attribute on any of their elements.\n• If there are conditions where some rows or columns are hidden or not present in the DOM, e.g., data is dynamically loaded when scrolling or the grid provides functions for hiding rows or columns, the following properties are applied as described in the\nGrid and Table Properties Practice .\n• aria-colcount or aria-rowcount is set to the total number of columns or rows, respectively.\n• aria-colindex or aria-rowindex is set to the position of a cell within a row or column, respectively.\n• If the grid includes cells that span multiple rows or multiple columns, and if the grid role is NOT applied to an HTML table element, then aria-rowspan or aria-colspan is applied as described in the\nGrid and Table Properties Practice .\nNote\n• If the element with the grid role is an HTML table element, then it is not necessary to use ARIA roles for rows and cells because the HTML elements have implied ARIA semantics.\nFor example, an HTML <TR> has an implied ARIA role of row .\nA grid built from an HTML table that includes cells that span multiple rows or columns must use HTML rowspan and colspan and must not use aria-rowspan or aria-colspan .\n• If rows or cells are included in a grid via aria-owns , they will be presented to assistive technologies after the DOM descendants of the grid element unless the DOM descendants are also included in the aria-owns attribute."
            }
          ],
          "links": [
            {
              "kind": "docs",
              "label": null,
              "url": "https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/grid/"
            },
